'''Romanesque Revival architecture''', '''Norman Revival architecture''' or '''Neo-Norman''' styles of building were inspired by the [[Romanesque Architecture]] of the 11th and 12th centuries AD. [[File:WiltonChurch.jpg|thumb|300px|Church of SS Mary and Nicholas, Wilton, Wiltshire, by TH Wyatt, 1841–4]] In the United Kingdom it started to appear as an architectural style in the 18th. century but reached its greatest popularity in the mid to latter years of the 19th. century. The style can be viewed as a strand of [[Gothic Revival architecture]] and part of the [[Historicism (art)|Historicist or Historismus]] styles of architecture that became popular in both Europe and Britain during the 19th. century. Early examples of the style in Germany of the 1820s and 1830s are referred to as [[Rundbogenstil]] or round arched style.{{sfn|Stratton|1993|pp=54–56}} In Britain the style was introduced by architects and their patrons, who had been on tours in Europe and it appears that the German and British styles of Romanesque developed largely independently. Initially in Britain the style was used for church building, but as the 19th. century progressed it was adapted for public buildings, museums, schools and commercial buildings, but rarely for domestic buildings. By the start of the 20th. century it had gone out of fashion and only occasionally were examples of the style built. [[File:Aubourn Church - geograph.org.uk - 863629.jpg|thumb|250px|Aubourn Church, Lincolnshire, 1862–3]]
== The origins of the Romanesque Revival or Norman Revival in the United Kingdom == [[File:St. Nicholas, Kenilworth, west door.jpg|thumb|left|St. Nicholas, Kenilworth, west door 1570]] [[File:North Scarle, Lincolnshire.jpg|thumb|150px|North Scarle, Lincolnshire]] The development of the ''Norman'' revival style or ''Neo-Norman'' took place over a long time in the British Isles starting with [[Inigo Jones]]‘s [[Window|re-fenestration]] of the White Tower of the [[Tower of London]] in 1637–38 and work at Windsor Castle by [[Hugh May]] for [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], but this was little more than restoration work. More surprising is the west door of Kenilworth Church, inserted in the tower in 1570 probably at the time of a visit of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]]. This appears to have been historic arch, sourced possibly from an unknown monastic building,<ref>''Country Life'', 12 January 2016</ref> Another early example of Romanesque revival is the south porch of North Scarle Church in Lincolnshire. Pevsner suggests that it might be Elizabethan, but late 17th. century seems more likely as the oak door seems to be original and probably of that date.{{sfn|Antram|Pevsner|Harris|1989|p=587}}
[[File:Culzean Castle house and gardens 01.JPG|thumb|left|Culzean Castle by Robert Adam, 1771]] [[File:St Martin's Church, Allerton Mauleverer. - geograph.org.uk - 419918.jpg|thumb|St Martin's Church, Allerton Mauleverer. - by John Vardy, 1745]]
In the 18th century the use of round arched windows was thought of as being [[Saxon]] rather than Norman and examples of buildings with round arched windows include [[Shirburn Castle]] in Oxfordshire, Wentworth in Yorkshire and [[Enmore Castle]] in Somerset. At [[Allerton Mauleverer]] in Yorkshire St Martin’s Church was re-built for Richard Arundell in 1745. The church has been described as a ''proto-Neo-Norman''. While it gives the impression of a Romanesque revival church, with a massive crossing tower and round headed windows, yet it also has windows with gothic tracery and a [[hammerbeam roof|hammerbeam]] nave roof. The architect is thought to have been [[John Vardy]] surveyor to the Office of Works.<ref>{{harvnb|Leach|Pevsner|2009|p=}}{{page needed|date=May 2018}}</ref> [[File:Tickencote Church - geograph.org.uk - 63353.jpg|thumb|225px|Tickencote Church 1792 Early example of church Romanesque revival]] A further example of church building in the Romanesque revival style took place in 1792 when Elisa Wingfield commissioned plans from [[Samuel Pepys Cockerell]] for the conservation and rebuilding of [[St Peter's Church, Tickencote]] in Rutland. The church which contained much notable Romanesque decoration and an elaborate [[chancel]] arch appears to have been close to collapse. Cockerell encased the chancel, keeping the arch in position but the outer walls were completely re-built and the exterior ornamentation of arcades and round headed windows were replaced in new stonework. A new tower over a porch was built on the south side, which gave added stability to the older structure. The [[nave]] was completely re-built using some new romanesque mot is and copying others, such as the engaged columns, from those on the exterior of the chancel.<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Page |editor-first=William |editor-link=William Page (historian) |year=1935 |chapter=Tickencote |title=A History of the County of Rutland |volume=II |series=[[Victoria County History]] |place=London |publisher=St Catherine Press |pages=275–281 |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/rutland/vol2/pp275-281 |accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref> This style of Romanesque revival architecture is very similar to the style that emerges in the 1840’s under architectects such as [[Thomas Penson]] and [[Benjamin Ferrey]]. Tickencote could be considered to mark the start of the Romanesque revival in church architecture. [[File:Front entrance to Eastnor Castle - geograph.org.uk - 1468597.jpg|thumb|left|Front entrance to Eastnor Castle, Herefordshire, combining Romanesque and Gothic features]] In Scotland the style started to emerge with the Duke of Argyll’s castle at [[Inverary]], started in 1744, and castles by [[Robert Adam]] at [[Culzean]] (1771), Oxenfoord (1780–2), Dalquharran (1782–5), and [[Seton Palace]] (1792). In England [[James Wyatt]] used round arched windows at [[Sandleford Priory]], Berkshire in 1780–79 and the Duke of Norfolk started to rebuild [[Arundel Castle]], while [[Eastnor Castle]] in Herefordshire was built by [[Robert Smirke (architect)|Robert Smirke]] between 1812 and 1820. At Eastnor Smirke combines a rugged Romanesque with more subtle Gothic window tracery.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mowl |first=Timothy |authorlink=Timothy Mowl |year=1981 |title=The Norman Revival in British Architecture 1790–1870}} PhD Thesis, [[University of Oxford]]</ref> {{clear}}
==The Development of ''Archaeologically Correct'' Romanesque.<ref>The idea of the ''archaeological correctness'' was popularised by [[Nikolaus Pevsner]] in his many writings and he was using the term by 1950 in his Broadcast Talks (page 190) to describe architecture and designs based closely on illustrations of actual buildings or objects.[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q8eaBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq=Pevsner+archaeologically+correct&source=bl&ots=xkM10Y0f1I&sig=gKtc0zp0nG3E71Al_PHmcJZFk5o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiuiKPAvJfKAhXIYQ4KHR3hCJwQ6AEIHzAA#v=onepage&q=Pevsner%20archaeologically%20correct&f=false]</ref>== [[File:GosfordCastle.jpg|thumb|left|GosfordCastle, Armagh by Thomas Hopper]] [[File:Penrhyn Castle - geograph.org.uk - 206536.jpg|thumb|Penrhyn Castle - by Thomas Hopper 1820–37]] It was at this point that the Norman Revival became a recognisable architectural style. In 1817 [[Thomas Rickman]] published his ''An Attempt to Discriminate the Styles of English Architecture from the Conquest to the Reformation''. It was now realised that ''round-arch architecture'' was largely Romanesque in the British Isles and came to be described as Norman rather than Saxon. This distinction was finally recognised when Rickman’s article in ''Archaeologia'' (1832–33), was published by the [[Society of Antiquaries of London|Society of Antiquaries]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Rickman |first=Thomas |title=` |journal=Archaeologia |volume=XXV |publisher=[[Society of Antiquaries of London]] |pages=159–185}} esp. 166</ref> The start of an ''archaeologically correct'' Norman Revival can be recognised in the architecture of [[Thomas Hopper (architect)|Thomas Hopper]]. His first attempt at this style was at [[Gosford Castle]] in Armagh in Ireland, but far more successful was his [[Penrhyn Castle]] near Bangor in North Wales. This was built for the Pennant family, between 1820 and 1837. The style did not catch on for domestic buildings, though many country houses and mock castles were built in the Castle Gothic or Castellated style during the Victorian period, which were mixed Gothic styles.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mowl |first=Timothy |authorlink=Timothy Mowl |year=1991 |chapter=Penrhryn and the Norman Revival |series=National Trust Guide |title=Penrhryn Castle, Gwynedd |place= |publisher=National Trust |pages=89–90}}</ref>
==Church Architecture and the Romanesque Revival== [[File:Church of St Agatha, Llanymynech 02.jpg|thumb|left|St Agatha, [[Llanymynech]]. Romanesque Tower by Penson 1845]] [[File:Rhosllanerchrugog Church.jpeg|thumb|Rhosllanerchrugog Church, 1852]] [[File:Christ Church, Welshpool. Chancel arcade in apse behind altar.JPG|thumb|Christ Church, Welshpool. Chancel arcade in apse behind altar]] However, the ''Norman Revival'' did catch on for church architecture. It was [[Thomas Penson]], a Welsh architect, who would have been familiar with Hopper’s work at Penrhyn, who developed Romanesque Revival church architecture. Penson was influenced by French and Belgian Romanesque architecture, and particularly the earlier Romanesque phase of German [[Brick Gothic]]. At St David’s Newtown, 1843–47 and St Agatha’s Llanymynech, 1845, he copies the tower of [[St. Salvator's Cathedral]], Bruges. Other examples of Romanesque revival by Penson are [[Christ Church, Welshpool]], 1839–1844, and the porch to Langedwyn Church. He was an innovator in the use of [[Architectural terracotta|terracotta]] to produce decorative Romanesque mouldings, saving on the expense of stonework.{{sfn|Stratton|1993|p=13}} Penson’s last church in the Romanesque Revival style was [[Rhosllannerchrugog]], Wrexham of 1852<ref>{{cite book |last=Hubbard |first=E |series=The Buildings of Wales |title=Clwyd |place=London |publisher=Penguin |year=1986 |page=264 |isbn=}}</ref>
===Sarah Losh and Wreay Church=== A most remarkable example of Romanesque church building was [[St Mary's Church, Wreay|St Mary’s Church at Wreay]], near Carlisle.<ref name=Banerjee>{{cite web |url= http://www.victorianweb.org/art/architecture/losh/1.html |last=Banerjee |first=Jacqueline |title=St Mary's Church, Wreay, by Sarah Losh (1785–1853) |publisher=Victorian Web |accessdate=}}</ref> This was designed by [[Sarah Losh]] and built between 1841 and 1842. Losh had travelled widely on the Continent and particularly in Italy and drew inspiration from Romanesque sources. Losh is known to have read [[Thomas Hope (architect)|Thomas Hope]]'s ''Historical Study of Architecture'' (1815), which uses the term ''Lombardic'' for the style brought into Italy from the early Christian churches of Constantinople, and she described St Mary's as being an ''unpolished mode of building'' that ''most approximates to early Saxon or modified Lombard''<ref>{{cite book |last=Uglow |first=Jenny |authorlink=Jenny Uglow |year=2012 |title=The Pinecone: the Story of Sara Losh |place=London |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |isbn=978-0571269501 |page=231}}</ref> This statement suggests that at the time of its design Losh was not aware of Thomas Rickman’s re-classification of Saxon and Norman architecture. While the appearance and layout of the church may be considered as Romanesque, her free interpretation of the decoration on the woodwork and the arched stone windows and doors is anticipating the styles of the [[Arts and Crafts]] movement, while the arcading of the [[apse]] certainly has a [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine]] feel to it.<ref name=Banerjee/>
===Sarah Losh Gallery=== {| align="center" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="4" style="border: 2px solid #9d9d9d;background-color:#eeeeee" valign="midlle" |- | <div align="centre"><gallery perrow="4"> File:St. Mary's Church Wreay, side view - geograph.org.uk - 561277.jpg|South side of St Mary's Church, Wreay File:Main Door, St Mary's Church, Wreay - geograph.org.uk - 174080.jpg|Main door of St Mary's Church File:Wreay Church - window surround with shells and pine cones - geograph.org.uk - 561740.jpg|A window of St Mary's Church, surrounded with reliefs of shells and pine cones File:St. Mary's Church Wreay, altar and part of apse - geograph.org.uk - 561294.jpg|Inside St Mary's arcaded, apsidal chancel</gallery> |}
==Other Early Victorian Architects working in the Romanesque revival style== The early years of the 1840s saw a considerable upsurge of interest in the developing Romanesque revival style by some of the leading architects of the period. During the 19th century the architecture selected for Anglican churches depended on the churchmanship of particular congregations. Whereas [[high church]]es and [[Anglo-Catholic]], which were influenced by the [[Oxford Movement]], were built in [[Gothic Revival architecture]]; low churches and [[Broad church]]es of the period were often built in the Romanesque Revival style.<ref>{{cite book |last=Clark|first=Kenneth|authorlink=Kenneth Clark|pages=170–73|title=The Gothic Revival|edition=3rd|year=1962 |publisher=John Murray|location=London|isbn= 0719502330}}, and also Cambridge Camden Society (1841),''A Few Words to Church-builders''[https://archive.org/details/fewwordstochurch00camb].</ref> The architects specialising in Romanesque revival took their designs from different local styles of the European Romanesque.
===Edmund Sharpe=== Another architect who popularised the Romanesque revival style was [[Edmund Sharpe]], who set up his practice at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] in 1835. At Cambridge he had been a great friend of [[William Whewell]] and presumably of the polymath and architectural historian Professor [[Robert Willis (engineer)|Robert Willis]]. He was awarded a travelling scholarship to study the early architecture of Germany and Southern France and supplied [[Thomas Rickman]] with information.<ref name=dnb>O'Donoghue, F. M. (1897), rev. Geoffrey K. Brandwood (2004) [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/25228 Sharpe, Edmund (1809–1877)], ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', [[Oxford University Press]], Retrieved on 18 February 2012 ({{ODNBsub}})</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Brandwood|Austin|Hughes|Price|2012|pp=12–15}}</ref> However, Sharpe despite being an architectural historian of some note, built churches that were much freer interpretations of the Romanesque and [[Brick Gothic|German Brick Gothic]] and might be considered less ''archaeologically correct''. [[File:St Mark the Evangelist, Witton - Church of England (geograph 2643308).jpg|thumb|left|St Mark's Church, Whitton, Blackburn]] [[File:St Paul's Parish Church, Scotforth, Doorway - geograph.org.uk - 904970.jpg|thumb|St Paul's, Scotforth, Doorway, 1874–6]] Four of Sharpe's earliest churches&nbsp;– [[St Saviour's Church, Cuerden|St&nbsp;Saviour, Bamber Bridge]] (1836–37);<ref>{{harvnb|Hughes|2010|p=116}}{{clarification needed |reason=What work is this citing? |date=May 2018}}</ref> [[St Mark's Church, Blackburn|St&nbsp;Mark, Witton]] (1836–38); and [[St Paul's Church, Farington|St&nbsp;Paul, Farington]], near [[Leyland, Lancashire|Leyland]] (1839–40)<ref>{{harvnb|Hughes|2010|p=125}}{{clarification needed |reason=What work is this citing? |date=May 2018}}</ref> – were in the Romanesque style, which he chose because ''no style can be worked so cheap as the Romanesque''. They ''turned out to be little more than rectangular 'preaching boxes'… with no frills and little ornamentation; and many of them were later enlarged''. The only subsequent churches in which Sharpe used Romanesque elements [[St Mary's Church, Conistone]] in [[Wharfedale]] (1846); and [[St Paul's Church, Scotforth|St&nbsp;Paul, Scotforth]] in south Lancaster (1874–6). Sharpe's final essay in the Romanesque Revival style [[St Paul's Church, Scotforth]], was described by [[Nikolaus Pevsner]] as a ''strange building'' and ''an anachronism, almost beyond belief''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1969 |title=Lancashire |volume=2 The Rural North |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |place=Harmondsworth |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |pages=29, 224}}</ref> Sharpe had retired from his architectural practice in 1851 He then pursued a career in railway engineering.<ref>O'Donoghue, F. M., rev. Geoffrey K. Brandwood, (2004) [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/25228 Sharpe, Edmund (1809–1877)], ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', [[Oxford University Press]] , Retrieved on 18 August 2009 {{ODNBsub}}</ref> In 1874, when he was aged 68, he returned to architecture and designed this church which was opened in 1876.{{sfn|Hartwell|Pevsner|2009|p=401}}{{sfn|Brandwood|Austin|Hughes|Price|2012|p=47}} The church had used terracotta in a similar fashion to his earliest churches and it can only be assumed that its anachronistic appearance was that he had used a design that he had prepared at least 20 years earlier.<ref>See Stratton, 1993, pages 50–52 for a discussion of the early use of [[architectural terracotta]] in the ''pot'' churches of Sharpe and Penson.</ref>
===Romanesque by Sharpe=== {| align="center" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="4" style="border: 2px solid #9d9d9d;background-color:#eeeeee" valign="midlle" |- | <div align="centre"><gallery perrow="5"> File:Porch, Parish of Christ Church, Chatburn - geograph.org.uk - 465172.jpg|Porch, Parish of Christ Church, Chatburn File:Christ Church, Chatburn.jpg|Christ Church, Chatburn File:St Paul's Church, Farington Moss.jpg|St Paul's Church, Farington Moss File:St Paul's Church, Scotforth.jpg|St Paul's Church, Scotforth File:St Paul's Parish Church Scotforth, Building detail - geograph.org.uk - 896858.jpg|St Paul's Scotforth, Arcaded apse </gallery> |}
===Benjamin Ferrey=== [[File:East Grafton - St Nicholas Church - geograph.org.uk - 1448466.jpg|thumb|left|East Grafton - St Nicholas Church, 1842–44]] [[File:Morpeth, Northumberland, The Church of St James The Great - geograph.org.uk - 223562.jpg|thumb|Morpeth, Northumberland, The Church of St James The Great, 1844–46]] The work of [[Benjamin Ferrey]] can be considered to be similar to that of Thomas Penson, based on the English and French Romanesque traditions. An early example is his church of St Nicholas at [[East Grafton]] in Wiltshire, built in 1842–44.<ref>{{cite web|website=Wiltshire Community History|title=Church of St. Nicholas, East Grafton|url=http://history.wiltshire.gov.uk/community/getchurch.php?id=1184|publisher=Wiltshire Council|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref> Here the chancel terminates in an apse and the west has overlapping arcading and [[Chevron (insignia)|chevron]] decoration over the entrance door. Central crossing tower and arcaded windows on the west frontis approached through a stone Romanesque [[Lych gate]].
A more important work by Ferrey is the Church of St James the Great at [[Morpeth, Northumberland|Morpeth]], Northumberland. The church, which is supposed to be modelled on the cathedral of [[Monreale]] in Sicily,<ref>{{cite book |last=Tweddle |first=Marilyn |title=A Historical Guide to the Church of St James the Great |place=Morpeth}}</ref> was built between 1844 and 1846. The unusual arched gate is acceptably Sicilian in inspiration and is similar to the [[portico]] at the cathedral at [[Monreale]], but the rest of the composition has much more in common with French and Belgian Romanesque. A further church in this style is Christ Church in [[Melplash]] in Dorset of 1845–46. This has a heavy crossing tower and in many respects resembles the Church of St. James the Great at Morpeth. {{clear}}
===Romanesque by Ferrey=== {| align="center" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="4" style="border: 2px solid #9d9d9d;background-color:#eeeeee" valign="midlle" |- | <div align="centre"><gallery perrow="5"> File:East Grafton - St Nicholas Church - geograph.org.uk - 1448460.jpg|East Grafton - St Nicholas Church chancel and apse 1842–44 File:East Grafton - Lych Gate - geograph.org.uk - 1448456.jpg|East Grafton - Lych Gate File:Gateway to The Church of St James the Great in Morpeth - geograph.org.uk - 1533881.jpg|Gateway to The Church of St James the Great in Morpeth File:St James' Church, Morpeth.jpg|St James' Church, Morpeth File:Melplash, Christ Church - geograph.org.uk - 451925.jpg|, Christ Church, Melplash, Doset </gallery> |}
{{clear}} ===William Perkin of Leeds=== St Michael and All Angels [[Barton le Street]], North Yorkshire. This church was very extensively rebuilt in 1869–71 by William Perkin and his sons of Leeds. Unlike Tickencote there is no record of the church that was replaced. The building contains an extensive and impressive range of genuine romanesque, but these seem to have been largely repositioned. The pews and some other furnishings are in Romanesque revival style. The rebuilding was financed by [[Hugo Francis Meynell Ingram|Hugo Francis Meynell-Ingram]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1966 |title=Yorkshire: the North Riding |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |place=Harmondsworth |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |isbn=0-14-071029-9 |page=73}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE| num=1148993 |desc=Church of St Michael |grade=I |accessdate=}}</ref>
